post_text: Dansville High School senior Olivia Calderone met with the Region IV FFA officer team. They are planning a leadership event for all FFA chapters in the Region. In her role as the Reporter, she is asked to create promotional materials and get the word out to all regional members. With COVID-19 restrictions in place, she and her team are working hard to plan an event where they can keep everyone safe while learning some new leadership skills and having a great time. Thanks for your hard work, Olivia! #StrongerTogether

Dansville Schools is doing our best to do everything we can to make this return to school as successful as possible. Doing this work has stretched us beyond anything we've ever experienced, so it is important for us to pause to reiterate that your kindness, benefit of the doubt, flexibility and patience have made all the difference as we continue into this launch of school. THANK YOU!

We are looking forward to seeing you all as we have a safe Aggie Family Reunion this week! #AggieFamily

post_text:
Take 10 minutes to fill out the census today!

The Michigan Department of Environment, Great Lakes, and Energy encourages you to participate in the 2020 Census.
Take ten minutes to fill out the Census today. The Census count will shape Michigan's social infrastructure for the next decade. If you need assistance completing the 2020 Census questionnaire, please call toll-free 1-844-330-2020.

To fill out the 2020 Census online visit: https://my2020census.gov/.

An accurate Census count is critical as it determines how much funding Michigan communities will receive for essential services through 2030 such as police, fire departments, health care, education, roads and infrastructure.

Help spread the word to your family members, friends and neighbors that responding to the Census is vital to Michigan’s future success.

For more information about the 2020 U.S. Census, visit https://my2020census.gov/.

Before we wrap up this year’s Dansville FFA Chapter Banquet, we want to introduce our new Agriscience Teacher and FFA Advisor, Mr. Mike Sheridan! Mr. Sheridan and his wife, Ginni, live right here in Dansville, and they are both active in the agriculture industry.

Mr. Sheridan has a passion for FFA and we can’t wait to see what the future holds with Mr. Sheridan and the Dansville FFA Chapter!

Have a great summer and stay safe!

We are continuing to offer free breakfast and lunch meals throughout the month of June on Tuesdays and Fridays, but please note that starting today, the hours will be slightly different, as we will be behind the elementary cafeteria from 11 AM until 12:30 PM. Please let me know if you need a delivery.

The exciting addition to this program for the month of June is that we will be offering free fresh produce and dairy boxes as Dansville Schools has partnered with the USDA's Farms to Families Program.

Tuesdays we will distribute the fresh produce boxes filled with approximately 25 pounds of amazing produce and Fridays we will distribute the dairy boxes to the first 100 families to pick up their meals. Today's box includes cheese slices, shredded cheese and butter!

#AggieFamily

In light of the Governor's executive order related to outdoor facilities, we are ready to reopen the district's outdoor track for the community. We will have signage posted in the morning at the outdoor track entry reminding those who enter that social distancing must be followed.

If we find that groups are congregating and not following social distancing, we may have to close the track, so please be sure to keep at least six feet between you and anyone else who enters the outdoor track area. We are not yet ready to reopen other outdoor areas, but we will continue to communicate as we move forward.

Thank you so much for your patience as we continue to work on our plans for reopening and restarting while also prioritizing the safety of all Aggies.

#AggieFamily

post_text:
Dansville students recently competed in Farmers State Bank's Student Art Contest.

The exhibition gives student artists a professional space in which to share their work with the community and aims to facilitate conversation about the value of the arts as an integral part of every student's educational experience.

Congratulations to Grand Prize winner Sophie Lindsay, High School winner Hailee Fry, Middle School winner Christina Williams and Elementary Winners Kennadee Griffes and Paisley Shirley.

In addition to receiving a gift card and ribbon, these students will have their artwork displayed in a Farmer's State Bank branch office for the next year.

#AggieFamily #AggieAchievers #TalentedAggies

Bethany Hamilton inspires me to always do what I love, and never let anything stop me.

Philosophy
Work hard today to unlock the doors , so you can open in them in the future

The hate you give, by Angie Thomas.

I plan on going to Michigan tech to study environmental engineering and minor in science.

PLEASE NOTE THIS CHANGE: we are giving boxes with 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches per student instead of 4! This means on Friday we will be distributing two days of breakfast and lunch meals instead of three.

We are happy to share that we will continue to provide meals and other supplies throughout the month of June, after school is out. We will send more details in the weeks to come, but wanted you to know we are going to make this happen to continue to support our Aggie Family!

Friday, May 8th is Food Distribution Day! We will have free breakfast and lunch meals, as well as extra food, books, school and hygiene supplies available for children/students 18 and under and students with special needs who are 26 and under. Stop by the back of the elementary cafeteria (Door #3) between 11 AM and 1 PM to access any of these supplies!

Donations of books, school supplies, fresh food, non-perishable food, and hygiene supplies will be accepted from 9 AM until 10 AM at Door #3. We are so thankful to our amazing Aggie Family for your generous donations that allow us to also directly purchase the supplies we need to keep offering these resources to our families!

#AggieFamily

Michigan Department of Health and Human Services
May 6 at 2:32 PM ·

Low-income college students in Michigan who are enrolled in career or technical education programs are now eligible to receive food assistance benefits through a new State of Michigan initiative effective this week.

College students will be eligible for SNAP if they meet income and other program requirements and are enrolled at least half-time in an occupational program that leads to employment under the Strengthening Career & Technical Education for the Twenty-First Century Act of 2018.

Learn more at http://bit.ly/2WzwYdQ.

On May 15th, the Smithsonian will release the module called “COVID-19! How can I protect myself and others?” which will take youth through 7 experiments/activities they can do at home to better understand the science (and social science) of COVID-19. The module will be freely available in 20+ languages and will be disseminated nationally and globally by WHO, UNICEF, the Smithsonian, and the InterAcademy Partnership (the world’s collaboration among 130 national academies of sciences, engineering, and medicine).

Ele's Place - Capital Region
April 29 at 6:36 AM ·

During this time of increased anxiety due to COVID-19, it is especially important to support grieving children and take time to discuss the current public health crisis. Children who have had significant losses may have stronger reactions, particularly if their losses involved a long illness. Offer reassurance about children’s safety, emphasizing that these incidents are rare. Talk about public health measures and community helpers.

If you need assistance about how to start this conversation and others like it, our clinical program staff is available to help! Please call us at (517) 482-1315.

Today, Tuesday April 28, is Food Distribution Day from 11 AM until 1 PM at Door #3 behind the elementary cafeteria. Please join us for free breakfast and lunch for all children 18 and under, as well as students with special needs who are 26 and under.

We also have extra bags of food, books, school and hygiene supplies for families.

If you need delivery, either once or every time, please don't hesitate to contact Superintendent Amy Hodgson at hodgson@dansville.org and we will get that arranged.

Check out Dansville Schools' Aggie K-12 Electives page where you can find weekly lesson plans for art, music, physical education and STEAM!

Your student doesn’t need to be enrolled in our classes to benefit from these activities and now is a great opportunity for all of our Aggies to spend time in each of these important areas. All students are able to participate in most of these lessons, which allows families to do these together!

We would LOVE to see your art projects, musical performances, physical activity workouts and STEAM projects!

Please post and tag Dansville Schools or your elective teacher!

Thanks so much for spending these next several weeks with us!

Mrs. Hekman, Mrs. McNabb, Mr. Felsing and Mrs. St. Amant

Dansville Schools Education Foundation
April 20 at 2:15 PM ·

Out of an abundance of caution for the health and safety of our community, and in respect of the immense strain the COVID-19 pandemic is placing on the families and small businesses who graciously support us every year, DSEF’s board has made the difficult decision to cancel our 2020 Dinner and Auction scheduled for November 7, 2020.

Like our incredible community, our board is working hard to adapt to our rapidly changing environment. We are actively working to develop innovative ways to continue to fulfill our mission to support high academic standards and excellence in teaching in Dansville Schools this year. We will provide updates as events continue to unfold and we will be in touch soon with ways to continue supporting Dansville Schools.

We thank you for your continued support of our organization, our schools and our community and look forward to coming together once again for our 2021 Dinner and Auction.

Please do not hesitate to contact the DSEF board at dsef48819@gmail.com if you have any questions or if we can assist you in any way. #aggiefamily #aggiestrong

shared_text:
Wilson Talent Center
April 16 at 7:44 PM ·

The Wilson Talent Center was unable to host our annual Wall-of-Fame & Awards Dinner on March 12 as we prepared to close our school buildings the following day. This event is near and dear to the hearts of our students, staff and alumni. At this event we present scholarship monies to our graduating seniors. This year we were prepared to present over $27,000. We are going to take some time over the next several days to publicly recognize these deserving seniors.

Our next senior is Jonathan Daman from Dansville High School. Jonathan was in our Engineering Technologies program his junior year and Precision Machining Technology this year. He plans to continue his education at Lansing Community College and transfer to either MSU or FSU to study tooling/industrial design or mechanical engineering.

Jonathan is the recipient of both the Student Success Scholarship and the Capital Area Tooling Partnership Scholarship. Congratulations, Jonathan!

#InghamImpact #ProudofOurSeniors

Rep. Elissa Slotkin
April 16 at 3:49 PM ·

Calling all high school artists! Our office is excited to announce that we are extending the deadline for submissions for the Congressional Arts Competition through May 7th. Visit our website for more information and to submit your artwork: https://bit.ly/2XGj7oh

We’ll then be holding a virtual exhibit to showcase students’ work –– so stay tuned! The winning artist will have their artwork displayed for one year in the Cannon Tunnel of the U.S. Capitol and will be flown to Washington, D.C., for a reception and award ceremony. The top three finalists will have their artwork displayed in our district offices. Can’t wait to see your submissions!

Know any talented high school artists in the 8th district? Feel free to tag them in the comments below:

#aggiefamily #inthistogether

Disaster Distress Helpline – 1-800-985-5990
This 24/7/365 service from the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration provides crisis counseling for people going through both natural and human-caused disasters. It’s free, multi-lingual and confidential. You can also text TalkWithUs to 66746.

National Suicide Prevention Hotline
If you’re feeling alone and struggling, you can also reach out toThe Crisis Text Line by texting TALK to 741741 or National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-TALK

Other statewide resources
2-1-1 — Call 2-1-1 from any phone to be connected to a list of statewide resources for everything from food and diapers to rental assistance and bus fare. You can also search their online database.

https://www.michigan.gov/documents/mdch/MIChild_Online_1_193650_7.pdf

The Wilson Talent Center was unable to host our annual Wall-of-Fame & Awards Dinner on March 12 as we prepared to close our school buildings the following day. This event is near and dear to the hearts of our students, staff and alumni. At this event we present scholarship monies to our graduating seniors. This year we were prepared to present over $27,000. Our next featured senior is Isaac Stec from Dansville High School who is completing our Automotive Technology program. Isaac plans to attend the University of Northwestern Ohio to become an agricultural equipment and diesel technician.

Isaac is the recipient of the WTC Motorsports Team Scholarship as well as the Colin Nethaway Memorial Scholarship. Congratulations, Isaac!

April 15 at 6:26 AM ·

During this time of increased anxiety due to COVID-19, it is especially important to support grieving children and take time to discuss the current public health crisis. The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) encourages parents, teachers, child care providers, and others who work closely with children to filter information about the crisis and present it in a way that their child can accommodate, adjust to, and cope with.

If you need assistance about how to start this conversation and others like it, our clinical program staff is available to help! Please call us at (517) 482 - 1315.

shared_text:
MSU Science Festival
April 3 at 3:44 PM ·

Join the Science Festival Team on April 4th for our first digital event of the year, Ask a Scientist! Starting at 10am, we're joined by Dr. Elias Aydi. He'll be answering all of your astronomy-related questions, so come curious!

Dr. Aydi is a Research Associate at the Physics and Astronomy department at Michigan State University. He graduated from the University of Cape Town (South Africa) in 2018 with a PhD in Astronomy and got his Masters at Notre Dame University in Beirut. Elias's research interests involve working on eruptive stars and optical transients using a diversity of space-based and ground-based facilities.

Join the Science Festival Team on April 4th for our first digital event of the year, Ask a Scientist! Starting at 10am, we're joined by Dr. Elias Aydi. He'll be answering all of your astronomy-related questions, so come curious!

Dr. Aydi is a Research Associate at the Physics and Astronomy department at Michigan State University. He graduated from the University of Cape Town (South Africa) in 2018 with a PhD in Astronomy and got his Masters at Notre Dame University in Beirut. Elias's research interests involve working on eruptive stars and optical transients using a diversity of space-based and ground-based facilities.

Dansville Schools will be distributing supplemental food, hygiene items, books and school supplies on Friday, April 3 from 11 am to 1 pm at door 3 of Dansville Elementary School.

As more of our families are faced with increasingly difficult situations related to health and job security, we encourage everyone with children up to age 18 or with special needs students up to age 26, to come and take advantage of all of these free resources.

As we continue to reflect on how to keep everyone safe during this process, we have 2 new requests:

If possible, please empty a spot in your trunk for the school breakfast and lunch items to be placed.

If possible, please empty the front passenger seat for the other additional items to be placed. If this isn’t possible, please give this passenger a box to have in their laps for the additional items to be placed.

#aggiefamily

Ensuring that no child goes without food is considered an essential service under the Stay Home Stay Safe order. As planned, Dansville Schools has hygiene items, books, school supplies and meals available for any child under 18, as well as adults with special needs under 26. Pickup will continue on Tuesdays and Fridays 11 am to 1 pm. Please come to door 3 of Dansville Elementary School. Children do not need to be enrolled in Dansville Schools and do not need to be present.

We will serve one car at a time, so please be patient as we also do our best to abide by the CDC guidelines of social distancing. Everyone who is serving will be wearing masks as an added precaution, will have taken their temperatures, and will be wearing gloves to make this service as safe as possible.

#aggiefamily

Dansville Schools
February 12 at 12:07 PM ·

Dansville’s tuition-free begindergarten program assists children in developing skills for kindergarten the following year.

It is designed for students who are “young fives” and those who would benefit from time to grow academically, emotionally and socially before starting kindergarten.

To be eligible for Begindergarten, child must turn five before Dec. 1, 2020.

Visit www.dansville.org or call 517-623-6120 to pre-register. Dansville School is currently accepting Schools of Choice students.

post_text: Senior Levi Zeitz and junior Olivia Calderone represented the Dansville FFA at the Michigan Farm Bureau Legislative Conference at the Lansing Center, where they had an opportunity to meet and visit with Vice President Pence￼. #waytorepresent

post_text:
Different schools offer a variety of strengths and we realize how important it is that you learn about the various programming and characteristics of the schools in our county to allow you to make an informed choice for your children.

We think you’ll be pleased to learn more about all that our school has to offer -- from our small family atmosphere to our cutting edge technology -- and so much more!

We would love the chance to partner with you as you help your child learn and grow through school.

Please feel free to call, email or stop by any time, as we are more than happy to meet with you as you consider joining the Aggie Family! #aggiefamily #smallbutmighty

post_text: The Dansville Schools Board of Education enjoyed a performance by our saxophone quartet this evening. The quartet of Elizabeth Troia, Hugh Service, Myah Muscott and Markas Hamlin, has qualified for the Michigan School Band & Orchestra Association State Solo and Ensemble Festival. Thanks for sharing your music this evening! #smallbutmighty
